Dwarves of Aetheria: A Realistic Portrait
Dwarves are the toughest, most industrious, and most stubborn of the major races. They number far fewer than humans but are disproportionately influential due to their unmatched engineering, craftsmanship, and sheer endurance. Average lifespan is 400–650 years, with some elders reaching 800+. This longevity, combined with their deep cultural memory and clan loyalty, makes them incredibly resilient — but also slow to change and burdened by ancient grudges.
In the current age, dwarves live primarily in the eight major Great Holds and scattered colonies. Their civilization is defined by stone, forge, honor, and an unending struggle against the darkness below.
Social Structure
Dwarven society is clan-based, hierarchical, and deeply traditional.

Great Clans: Powerful bloodlines that rule entire holds or major districts. Clan loyalty supersedes almost everything.
Thanes & Runelords: The ruling nobility. A Thane governs a hold or large territory; Runelords are the spiritual and magical elite.
Master Artisans & Deep Guard: The respected middle class — smiths, engineers, miners, and elite warriors.
Common Dwarves: Stonecutters, brewers, farmers (in surface colonies), and laborers.
Stone-Bound (Slaves): Mostly debtors, criminals, or war captives. They perform the most dangerous underground work.

Status is earned through skill, deeds, and contributions to the clan. A low-born dwarf who forges a masterwork or slays a great beast can rise high. Politics are blunt, grudge-driven, and often settled by formal duels or votes in the Stone Council.
Core Cultural Values

Stone and Honor: “The mountain does not yield. Neither do we.” Dwarves value unyielding reliability, craftsmanship, and keeping one’s word.
Grudges and Memory: Insults or debts are recorded in the Book of Grudges. Some feuds have lasted over 4,000 years.
Craft and Legacy: Creating something that outlasts you is the highest goal. A well-made axe or hall is immortality.
Practicality: Dwarves are blunt, skeptical of fancy words, and suspicious of anything “too pretty” or magical without practical use.
Endurance: Pain, hardship, and long labor are badges of honor. Complaining is for weaker races.

Daily Life and Customs
Dwarven holds are vast underground cities of carved stone, glowing runes, and roaring forges. Life is communal and rhythmic.

Food: Heavy, rich, and filling — roasted meats, mushroom stews, stonebread, and vast quantities of ale and stout. Feasts are legendary.
Clothing: Practical and durable. Leather, wool, and reinforced chain or plate even for civilians. Master artisans wear finely detailed work clothes that double as status symbols.
Family: Strong nuclear and extended clans. Marriage is a serious clan alliance, though love matches occur. Children are raised collectively and taught a trade early.
Entertainment: Drinking songs, axe-throwing contests, storytelling around the great forges, and competitive stone-carving.
Death: Bodies are entombed in stone with their greatest creation or weapon. Ancestor worship is strong — spirits of great dwarves are believed to watch over the clan.

Religion
Dwarves honor the Twelve in a blunt, practical, and ancestor-focused manner. Religion is inseparable from daily labor and clan duty.

Karadun, the Deep Father is by far the most important — seen as the literal shaper of the mountains and patron of their entire race.
Korrak, the Iron Eternal – god of honorable war and unbreakable oaths.
Aetherion – respected as the source of mana that fuels their forges.
Nythera – honored during funerals and when sealing the dead in stone tombs.

Shrines are carved directly into forge walls and mine entrances. Prayers are short, sung as work chants, and often end with hammer strikes. Dwarves record divine favors (and grudges) in stone. They believe the gods respect those who endure and build lasting works. The demonic infestation of the Deep Holds is seen as a direct insult to Karadun, and many dwarves pray daily for the gods to finally turn their gaze downward and aid them.

Military Culture
Dwarves are masters of defensive warfare. They excel in tunnel fighting, siege defense, and brutal close-quarters combat.

Deep Guard: Elite professional soldiers who spend their lives underground.
Golem Legions: Small numbers of stone and iron constructs still support armies.
Axe & Hammer: Heavy infantry in rune-etched plate, supported by crossbows and siege engines.
Surface Clans: More mobile, often serving as mercenaries.

They are slow to attack but nearly impossible to dislodge once entrenched. Losses are mourned for generations.
Magic in Dwarven Society (1 in 4,000)
Magic is rare among dwarves — only about 1 in 4,000 births shows any real aptitude. This scarcity makes magical talent extremely valuable and respected, but also viewed with slight suspicion.

Most common aptitudes: Earth, Fire, Rune/Inscription, and minor Aetherforge remnants.
Training is long, rigorous, and tied directly to craftsmanship. A dwarf mage is almost always also a master smith or engineer.
Magic is seen as a tool, never an end in itself. The greatest mages focus on permanent enchantments, forge enhancement, and structural reinforcement.
Runelords (the magical elite) hold enormous status and often sit on ruling councils.
The loss of true Aetherforge Magic and high-level Rune Magic is a source of deep cultural regret. Many dwarves believe that rediscovering these would allow them to restore the full glory of Karadun.

Because magic is so rare, most dwarven wonders rely on engineering, skill, and hard work rather than spells.
Attitudes Toward Other Races

Humans: Useful allies and trading partners, but short-sighted and reckless. “Good fighters, terrible planners.”
Elves: Ancient rivals. Viewed as arrogant, fragile, and disconnected from honest labor. “Leaf-lovers who let trees do their work.”
Beastkin: Respected for strength and endurance (especially Ironhides), but considered wild and undisciplined.
Demons: Pure hatred. The underground war is existential. No mercy is ever given.

Dwarves are generally xenophobic but pragmatic — they will trade and ally when it benefits the clan or hold.
Economy and Outlook
Dwarven economy runs on mining, forging, engineering, and trade. They export the finest weapons, armor, tools, and machinery in Aetheria and import food, cloth, and luxuries. Internal trade between holds is strong, but each hold is largely self-sufficient.
Modern dwarves carry a heavy but determined mindset: they know the Golden Age is gone and much has been lost, yet they believe that through unyielding labor, perfect craftsmanship, and stubborn refusal to die, they can reclaim their rightful place beneath (and eventually above) the mountains.
In short, dwarves are the living embodiment of stone — hard, enduring, slow to move, but unbreakable once set in motion. Their culture prizes work, honor, and legacy above all else in a world that constantly tries to break them.

