Demons and Devils of Aetheria: A Realistic Portrait
Demons and Devils (collectively called Infernals by mortals) are not a single unified race but a chaotic collection of beings native to the lower planes who have carved out permanent territories on the material world. Their numbers are unknown and fluctuate wildly due to endless internal wars, summoning rituals, and corruption of mortal bloodlines. They are the most hated and feared force in Aetheria, yet they persist because of their raw power, adaptability, and the inability of mortals to fully exterminate them.
Demons tend to be more chaotic, monstrous, and destructive. Devils are more hierarchical, scheming, and lawful-evil. In practice, the distinction often blurs in the mortal realm.
Social Structure
Infernal society is brutal, hierarchical, and constantly shifting.

Demon Lords & Hell Princes: God-like tyrants who rule massive territories. Power is held through strength, cunning, fear, and pacts. A Lord can be overthrown at any moment.
Highbloods (the “civilized” caste): Succubi, incubi, horned aristocrats, and near-human demons with red/violet eyes, wings, tails, or obsidian skin. They serve as generals, diplomats, seducers, and administrators.
Legion Commanders & Pit Barons: Mid-tier monsters and warlords who control armies and fortresses.
Lesser Demons: The endless hordes — monstrous, bestial, or malformed creatures of fang, scale, chitin, and corrupted flesh.
Mortal Thralls & Hybrids: Enslaved humans, Beastkin, elves, etc., plus demonic half-breeds (cambions). Some rise to minor power; most are cattle.

Loyalty is transactional and temporary. Betrayal is expected and often rewarded if successful. Territories change hands through civil war far more often than through mortal crusades.
Core Cultural Values

Power is Truth: Strength, cunning, and the ability to dominate others are the only virtues. Weakness is disgusting.
Corruption and Dominion: Turning something pure (especially elven or Beastkin) into something monstrous is considered high art.
Pleasure through Suffering: Pain, fear, lust, and despair are delicious. Many demons literally feed on negative emotions.
Hierarchy through Terror: Respect is enforced through displays of overwhelming force.
Eternal Ambition: Every demon dreams of becoming a Lord or ascending to even darker planes.

Daily Life and “Culture”
There is no “normal” daily life — existence in demonic territories is nightmarish by mortal standards.

Strongholds: Black citadels, bone fortresses, rivers of blood, and flesh-crafted palaces. The Crimson Canopy and Abyssal Deeps are infamous.
“Food”: Souls, fresh mortal flesh, and harvested emotions. Highbloods enjoy fine wines mixed with blood and suffering.
Entertainment: Gladiatorial pits, torture gardens, orgies of violence and lust, and elaborate schemes against rivals.
Reproduction: Many lesser demons are spawned from corruption pools or summoned. Highbloods breed with mortals or each other to create useful hybrids.
Time: Demons experience time differently. Centuries pass like decades to them. A “short” civil war can last 200 years.

Religion
Demons do not worship gods — they aspire to become them. Many revere the First Fallen (ancient entities said to have existed before the world) or the Abyssal Overlords who dwell in the deepest hells.
Rituals revolve around blood sacrifice, soul-binding contracts, and grand displays of dominance. Highbloods sometimes maintain twisted mockeries of mortal religions for amusement or manipulation.
Military Culture
Demonic armies are overwhelming, relentless, and terrifying.

Hordes: Endless waves of lesser demons and corrupted monsters.
Highblood Legions: Disciplined elite troops led by succubi tacticians or winged shock troops.
Corruption Engines: Armies that spread taint as they march, turning the land and its people against themselves.
Tactics: Overwhelming force, psychological terror, betrayal from within, and attrition. They excel at sieges and guerrilla corruption.

They are weakest when forced into prolonged defensive wars or when their leader is assassinated.
Magic Among Demons (Frequency Unknown)
Magic is extremely common and powerful among infernals — far more than any mortal race. Exact ratios are unknown because their population is fluid and many are literally made of magic.

Common aptitudes: Dark, Infernal, Blood, Soul, Chaos, Void, and Emotion magic.
Highbloods frequently wield multiple schools with terrifying proficiency. Many can cast without chants through sheer willpower or pacts.
Demonic magic specializes in corruption, soul manipulation, summoning reinforcements, and reality-warping within their territories.
Lost mortal magics (Demon/ Infernal Magic, Blood Magic, etc.) are everyday tools for them. Some ancient demons still remember fragments of Golden Age sorcery.

Magic is not “rare talent” — it is their birthright and primary weapon.
Attitudes Toward Other Races

All Mortals: Prey. Elves and Beastkin are favorite targets because their suffering and corruption are especially satisfying.
Humans: Useful, numerous, and easily corrupted. Many demons see them as the best source of thralls and hybrid soldiers.
Dwarves: Annoying, stubborn meat. Their stone holds are difficult to crack but rich in resources.
Elves: The ultimate prize. Breaking an elf’s pride and purity is considered exquisite sport.
Other Demons: Rivals first, allies of convenience second. Trust is nonexistent.

Economy and Outlook
Demonic “economy” runs on souls, suffering, slave labor, and stolen resources. They raid for captives, magical reagents, and luxuries. Highblood courts maintain sophisticated (if cruel) trade with unscrupulous mortal merchants.
